A Logistic Regression for REDCON Bids

Jim Greene

April 11, 2019

This model can help predict if a bid will win.

# Enter values to test:
survey <- 45000
contract_total <- 800000
engineer_estimate <- 700000
days_open <- 3
number_of_bidders <- 2
# Enter values:
survey <- 45000
contract_total <- 800000
engineer_estimate <- 700000
days_open <- 3
number_of_bidders <- 2


setwd("C:/Users/Jim/Desktop/RedCon")
data <- read_csv("./Team Folder/master_data_derived_cols.csv")

# Correct some values
data$days_open[data$days_open < 0] <- 1
data$award_date[data$award_date < as.Date('2017-01-01')] <- as.Date('2018-03-27')

# # Check that there is only one occurance of each bidder per project
# max(table(data$project_number, data$bidder))

# Add column
data <- data %>% add_count(project_number)
# Rename new column
colnames(data)[19] <- "bidder_count"

# Reduce the data
data_r <- data[c(5,9:19)]

# 'unknown' column is actually the county
colnames(data_r)[1] <- "county"

# # Check for NAs
# sum(is.na(data_r$county))

# Change data type
data_r$county <- as.factor(data_r$county)

# Logistic Regression Model
glm8 <- glm(win ~ bidder_count:survey_percent_of_contract + survey_percent_of_contract:days_open + percent_of_EE, data = data_r, family = binomial)


# Compute probability
survey_percent_of_contract <- survey/contract_total
contract_percent_of_engineer_estimate <- contract_total/engineer_estimate

beta <- glm8$coef

estimated_prob <- 1/(1 + exp(-1*(beta[1] + beta[2]*contract_percent_of_engineer_estimate + beta[3]*survey_percent_of_contract*number_of_bidders + beta[4]*survey_percent_of_contract*days_open)))

pander(paste0("Estimated chance of winning: ", round(estimated_prob,5)*100, "%"))

Estimated chance of winning: 99.858%



Details

Model

\[ P(\text{winning bid}|\, \text{survey percent of contract}, \text{contract percent of engineer estimate}, \text{numer of bidders}, \text{days open}) = \\ (1+e^{-1(6.6484 - 0.0703 \times \text{contract percent of engineer estimate} -0.2443 \times \text{numer of bidders} \times \text{survey percent of contract} + 0.0842 \times \text{survey percent of contract} \times \text{days open})})^{-1} \]

Interpretation


It is estimated that the odds of winning changes by a factor of each of the following values on the left for each one unit increase in the final values of the functions on the right:

Coefficient Variable
771.5578 (cant be changed) baseline
0.9321 [contract total] [engineer estimate] 100
0.7832 [number of bidders] [survey] [contract total] 100
1.0878 [number of days the bid has been open] [survey] [contract total] 100

Validation

### Validation

n <- nrow(data_r)
trainrows <- sample(1:n, 300)

train <- data_r[trainrows, ]
test <- data_r[-trainrows, ]

testglm <- glm(win ~ bidder_count:survey_percent_of_contract + survey_percent_of_contract:days_open + percent_of_EE, data = train, family = binomial)

probs <- predict(testglm, test, type = "response")
predictions <- ifelse(probs > .5, 1, 0)
table(predictions, test$win)
##            
## predictions  0  1
##           0 69 14
##           1 14 14
pander(paste0("Classification Accuracy: ", round(mean(predictions == test$win), 5)))

Classification Accuracy: 0.74775
